</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Lynch syndrome is the most common hereditary cancer syndrome, the most common cause of heritable colorectal cancer, and the only known heritable cause of endometrial cancer. Other cancers associated with Lynch syndrome include cancers of the ovary, stomach, urothelial tract, and small bowel, and less frequently, cancers of the brain, biliary tract, pancreas, and prostate. The oncogenic tendency of Lynch syndrome stems from a set of genomic alterations of mismatch repair proteins. Defunct mismatch repair proteins cause unusually high instability of regions of the genome called microsatellites. Over time, the accumulation of mutations in microsatellites and elsewhere in the genome can affect the production of important cellular proteins, spurring tumorigenesis. Universal testing of colorectal tumors for microsatellite instability (MSI) is now recommended to <i>(a)</i> prevent cases of Lynch syndrome being missed owing to the use of clinical criteria alone, <i>(b)</i> reduce morbidity and mortality among the relatives of affected individuals, and <i>(c)</i> guide management decisions. Organ-specific cancer risks and associated screening paradigms vary according to the sex of the affected individual and the type of germline DNA alteration causing the MSI. Furthermore, Lynch syndrome–associated cancers have different pathologic, radiologic, and clinical features compared with their sporadic counterparts. Most notably, Lynch syndrome–associated tumors tend to be more indolent than non–Lynch syndrome–associated neoplasms and thus may respond differently to traditional chemotherapy regimens. The high MSI in cases of colorectal cancer reflects a difference in the biologic features of the tumor, possibly with a unique susceptibility to immunotherapy.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170075">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170075">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig1.jpeg" height="2036" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Diagram illustrates MSI. Top: When a mismatched loop of DNA is detected, it is properly repaired such that the original number of nucleotide repeats (five) is preserved. Bottom: Defective MMR results in different lengths of microsatellite nucleotide repeats in different cells after replication. In this case, one cell has three nucleotide repeats and the other cell has five. This variability in the length of microsatellite nucleotide repeats is referred to as instability.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig2a.jpeg" height="1643" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Immunohistochemical analysis of MMR proteins. <b>(a)</b> High-power photomicrograph of a CRC biopsy specimen shows diffuse immunoreactivity to the presence of MSH2 protein, as indicated by the brown-stained nuclei, which is consistent with normal <i>MSH2</i> expression. (Immunohistochemical stain for <i>MSH2;</i> original magnification, ×20.) <b>(b)</b> High-power photomicrograph of the same specimen shows a lack of immunoreactivity to <i>MLH1,</i> compatible with loss of <i>MLH1</i> expression. (Immunohistochemical stain for <i>MLH1;</i> original magnification, ×20.) The specimen is also counterstained with hematoxylin-eosin (blue-gray) to enhance visibility. Brown nuclear staining is present in normal (nontumor) cells such as lymphocytes and endothelial cells. The lack of <i>MLH1</i> staining in the tumor could be due to <i>MLH1</i> mutation or epigenetic silencing caused by hypermethylation. The next step would be to determine the <i>MLH1</i> methylation and <i>BRAF</i> mutation status. If tests for these processes yielded negative results, the patient would need to undergo germline testing for <i>MLH1</i> mutation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig2b.jpeg" height="1643" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Immunohistochemical analysis of MMR proteins. <b>(a)</b> High-power photomicrograph of a CRC biopsy specimen shows diffuse immunoreactivity to the presence of MSH2 protein, as indicated by the brown-stained nuclei, which is consistent with normal <i>MSH2</i> expression. (Immunohistochemical stain for <i>MSH2;</i> original magnification, ×20.) <b>(b)</b> High-power photomicrograph of the same specimen shows a lack of immunoreactivity to <i>MLH1,</i> compatible with loss of <i>MLH1</i> expression. (Immunohistochemical stain for <i>MLH1;</i> original magnification, ×20.) The specimen is also counterstained with hematoxylin-eosin (blue-gray) to enhance visibility. Brown nuclear staining is present in normal (nontumor) cells such as lymphocytes and endothelial cells. The lack of <i>MLH1</i> staining in the tumor could be due to <i>MLH1</i> mutation or epigenetic silencing caused by hypermethylation. The next step would be to determine the <i>MLH1</i> methylation and <i>BRAF</i> mutation status. If tests for these processes yielded negative results, the patient would need to undergo germline testing for <i>MLH1</i> mutation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig3.jpeg" height="1739" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Diagram illustrates the testing paradigm for cases of newly diagnosed CRC. MSI can be detected by performing immunohistochemical <i>(IHC)</i> analysis of MMR protein expression or polymerase chain reaction <i>(PCR)</i> sequencing of predefined microsatellite loci, depending on the institution’s preference. <i>LS</i> = Lynch syndrome, MSS = microsatellite stable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig4a.jpeg" height="1525" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Colorectal tumor development with potentially actionable mutations. <b>(a)</b> Drawing illustrates the classic adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence, which is frequently triggered by <i>APC</i> mutation. <b>(b)</b> Drawing illustrates tumor development when MSI is an initiating event.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig4b.jpeg" height="1414" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Colorectal tumor development with potentially actionable mutations. <b>(a)</b> Drawing illustrates the classic adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence, which is frequently triggered by <i>APC</i> mutation. <b>(b)</b> Drawing illustrates tumor development when MSI is an initiating event.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig5.jpeg" height="1245" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Endoscopic image obtained in a 66-year-old woman with an <i>MSH6</i> gene mutation shows a flat polyp (circled), which is typical with Lynch syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig6a.jpeg" height="1679" width="1671" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. High-MSI colonic adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Low-power photomicrograph shows a Crohn syndrome–like lymphoid reaction (arrowheads) in the pericolic fat <i>(PF),</i> below the muscularis propria <i>(MP)</i> and cancer <i>(CA).</i> (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×0.5.) <b>(b)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes (black arrows), characterized by hyperchromatic nuclei and scant cytoplasm, interspersed between the larger neoplastic cells (white arrows), which are exhibiting nucleomegaly and prominent nucleoli. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig6b.jpeg" height="1679" width="1678" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. High-MSI colonic adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Low-power photomicrograph shows a Crohn syndrome–like lymphoid reaction (arrowheads) in the pericolic fat <i>(PF),</i> below the muscularis propria <i>(MP)</i> and cancer <i>(CA).</i> (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×0.5.) <b>(b)</b> High-power photomicrograph shows tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes (black arrows), characterized by hyperchromatic nuclei and scant cytoplasm, interspersed between the larger neoplastic cells (white arrows), which are exhibiting nucleomegaly and prominent nucleoli. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig7a.jpeg" height="1085" width="1772" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Germline hypermethylation of the <i>MLH1</i> promoter in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a large mass (arrow) in the ascending colon. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused positron emission tomographic (PET)/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images obtained after surgical resection of the mass show fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG)–avid aortocaval lymphadenopathy (arrow), which represents metastasis. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after immunotherapy shows that the aortocaval lymph node (arrow) has decreased in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig7b.jpeg" height="2025" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Germline hypermethylation of the <i>MLH1</i> promoter in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a large mass (arrow) in the ascending colon. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused positron emission tomographic (PET)/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images obtained after surgical resection of the mass show fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG)–avid aortocaval lymphadenopathy (arrow), which represents metastasis. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after immunotherapy shows that the aortocaval lymph node (arrow) has decreased in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig7c.jpeg" height="1088" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Germline hypermethylation of the <i>MLH1</i> promoter in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a large mass (arrow) in the ascending colon. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused positron emission tomographic (PET)/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images obtained after surgical resection of the mass show fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG)–avid aortocaval lymphadenopathy (arrow), which represents metastasis. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after immunotherapy shows that the aortocaval lymph node (arrow) has decreased in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig7d.jpeg" height="1111" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Germline hypermethylation of the <i>MLH1</i> promoter in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a large mass (arrow) in the ascending colon. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused positron emission tomographic (PET)/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images obtained after surgical resection of the mass show fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG)–avid aortocaval lymphadenopathy (arrow), which represents metastasis. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after immunotherapy shows that the aortocaval lymph node (arrow) has decreased in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig7e.jpeg" height="1411" width="1563" aria-labelledby="fig7e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7e</span>. Germline hypermethylation of the <i>MLH1</i> promoter in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a large mass (arrow) in the ascending colon. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused positron emission tomographic (PET)/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images obtained after surgical resection of the mass show fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG)–avid aortocaval lymphadenopathy (arrow), which represents metastasis. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after immunotherapy shows that the aortocaval lymph node (arrow) has decreased in size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig8a.jpeg" height="1283" width="1395" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Endometrial adenocarcinoma in a 47-year-old woman with a history of heavy menstrual bleeding and abnormal cells seen at Papanicolaou smear testing. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a retroverted uterus and a 4-cm mass (thick arrows) involving the lower uterine segment and cervix and invading more than 50% of the thickness of the myometrium and cervix. The thin arrow in <b>a</b> points to the uterine fundus. Biopsy revealed endometrioid endometrial adenocarcinoma. The patient was examined for possible Lynch syndrome because of her age and two siblings who were diagnosed with CRC before age 40 years. She was found to be an <i>MSH2</i> mutation carrier.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig8b.jpeg" height="1283" width="1557" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Endometrial adenocarcinoma in a 47-year-old woman with a history of heavy menstrual bleeding and abnormal cells seen at Papanicolaou smear testing. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a retroverted uterus and a 4-cm mass (thick arrows) involving the lower uterine segment and cervix and invading more than 50% of the thickness of the myometrium and cervix. The thin arrow in <b>a</b> points to the uterine fundus. Biopsy revealed endometrioid endometrial adenocarcinoma. The patient was examined for possible Lynch syndrome because of her age and two siblings who were diagnosed with CRC before age 40 years. She was found to be an <i>MSH2</i> mutation carrier.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig9a.jpeg" height="1030" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma in a 47-year-old woman with a history of right lower quadrant pain and dysfunctional uterine bleeding. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(b)</b> images show an FDG-avid right ovarian mass (thick arrow), with the uterine fundus (thin arrow in <b>b</b>) pushed to the left. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images show a thickened and FDG-avid endometrium (arrows). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(e)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(f)</b> images show another FDG-avid mass (arrow) in the descending colon. At surgery, the patient was found to have grade 2 ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising in an endometrioid borderline tumor and grade 1 endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium arising in a background of complex atypical hyperplasia. The colonic mass is adenocarcinoma arising in a descending colon adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig9b.jpeg" height="1030" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma in a 47-year-old woman with a history of right lower quadrant pain and dysfunctional uterine bleeding. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(b)</b> images show an FDG-avid right ovarian mass (thick arrow), with the uterine fundus (thin arrow in <b>b</b>) pushed to the left. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images show a thickened and FDG-avid endometrium (arrows). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(e)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(f)</b> images show another FDG-avid mass (arrow) in the descending colon. At surgery, the patient was found to have grade 2 ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising in an endometrioid borderline tumor and grade 1 endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium arising in a background of complex atypical hyperplasia. The colonic mass is adenocarcinoma arising in a descending colon adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig9c.jpeg" height="1030" width="1472" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma in a 47-year-old woman with a history of right lower quadrant pain and dysfunctional uterine bleeding. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(b)</b> images show an FDG-avid right ovarian mass (thick arrow), with the uterine fundus (thin arrow in <b>b</b>) pushed to the left. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images show a thickened and FDG-avid endometrium (arrows). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(e)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(f)</b> images show another FDG-avid mass (arrow) in the descending colon. At surgery, the patient was found to have grade 2 ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising in an endometrioid borderline tumor and grade 1 endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium arising in a background of complex atypical hyperplasia. The colonic mass is adenocarcinoma arising in a descending colon adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig9d.jpeg" height="1030" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma in a 47-year-old woman with a history of right lower quadrant pain and dysfunctional uterine bleeding. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(b)</b> images show an FDG-avid right ovarian mass (thick arrow), with the uterine fundus (thin arrow in <b>b</b>) pushed to the left. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images show a thickened and FDG-avid endometrium (arrows). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(e)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(f)</b> images show another FDG-avid mass (arrow) in the descending colon. At surgery, the patient was found to have grade 2 ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising in an endometrioid borderline tumor and grade 1 endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium arising in a background of complex atypical hyperplasia. The colonic mass is adenocarcinoma arising in a descending colon adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig9e.jpeg" height="821" width="1472" aria-labelledby="fig9e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9e</span>. Ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma in a 47-year-old woman with a history of right lower quadrant pain and dysfunctional uterine bleeding. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(b)</b> images show an FDG-avid right ovarian mass (thick arrow), with the uterine fundus (thin arrow in <b>b</b>) pushed to the left. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images show a thickened and FDG-avid endometrium (arrows). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(e)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(f)</b> images show another FDG-avid mass (arrow) in the descending colon. At surgery, the patient was found to have grade 2 ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising in an endometrioid borderline tumor and grade 1 endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium arising in a background of complex atypical hyperplasia. The colonic mass is adenocarcinoma arising in a descending colon adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig9e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig9f.jpeg" height="821" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig9f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9f</span>. Ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma in a 47-year-old woman with a history of right lower quadrant pain and dysfunctional uterine bleeding. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(b)</b> images show an FDG-avid right ovarian mass (thick arrow), with the uterine fundus (thin arrow in <b>b</b>) pushed to the left. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(d)</b> images show a thickened and FDG-avid endometrium (arrows). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial fused FDG PET/CT <b>(e)</b> and contrast-enhanced CT <b>(f)</b> images show another FDG-avid mass (arrow) in the descending colon. At surgery, the patient was found to have grade 2 ovarian endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising in an endometrioid borderline tumor and grade 1 endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium arising in a background of complex atypical hyperplasia. The colonic mass is adenocarcinoma arising in a descending colon adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig9f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig10a.jpeg" height="1434" width="1483" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Urothelial cancer in a 50-year-old man with Lynch syndrome secondary to germline loss of <i>MSH2</i> and <i>MSH6,</i> who underwent surveillance CT after resection of colon cancer 1 year earlier. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows left hydronephrosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT images of the dilated left ureter show soft tissue filling the distal ureter (arrows), indicating urothelial cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig10b.jpeg" height="1434" width="1222" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Urothelial cancer in a 50-year-old man with Lynch syndrome secondary to germline loss of <i>MSH2</i> and <i>MSH6,</i> who underwent surveillance CT after resection of colon cancer 1 year earlier. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows left hydronephrosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT images of the dilated left ureter show soft tissue filling the distal ureter (arrows), indicating urothelial cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig10c.jpeg" height="1434" width="997" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Urothelial cancer in a 50-year-old man with Lynch syndrome secondary to germline loss of <i>MSH2</i> and <i>MSH6,</i> who underwent surveillance CT after resection of colon cancer 1 year earlier. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows left hydronephrosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT images of the dilated left ureter show soft tissue filling the distal ureter (arrows), indicating urothelial cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig11a.jpeg" height="926" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Gastric cancer in a 65-year-old woman with Lynch syndrome related to germline loss of <i>MLH1</i> and <i>PMS2,</i> who underwent colon cancer resection 21 years earlier and presented with atypical chest pain and symptoms of anemia. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show near-circumferential thickening of the gastric body (arrows), representing gastric cancer. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows FDG avidity of the tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig11b.jpeg" height="926" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Gastric cancer in a 65-year-old woman with Lynch syndrome related to germline loss of <i>MLH1</i> and <i>PMS2,</i> who underwent colon cancer resection 21 years earlier and presented with atypical chest pain and symptoms of anemia. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show near-circumferential thickening of the gastric body (arrows), representing gastric cancer. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows FDG avidity of the tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig11c.jpeg" height="1258" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Gastric cancer in a 65-year-old woman with Lynch syndrome related to germline loss of <i>MLH1</i> and <i>PMS2,</i> who underwent colon cancer resection 21 years earlier and presented with atypical chest pain and symptoms of anemia. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show near-circumferential thickening of the gastric body (arrows), representing gastric cancer. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows FDG avidity of the tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig12a.jpeg" height="944" width="1180" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Duodenal adenocarcinoma in a 63-year-old man with a history of three primary colon cancers diagnosed at ages 35, 40, and 53 years; duodenal cancer at age 46 years; and transitional cell carcinoma of the right ureter at age 58 years. Axial contrast-enhanced CT <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT <b>(b)</b> images show an ill-defined FDG-avid thickening of the transverse duodenum (arrows) invading the pancreas and mesentery. The patient was diagnosed with a second primary duodenal adenocarcinoma. He had germline mutations of <i>MSH2</i> and <i>MSH6.</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig12b.jpeg" height="943" width="1769" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Duodenal adenocarcinoma in a 63-year-old man with a history of three primary colon cancers diagnosed at ages 35, 40, and 53 years; duodenal cancer at age 46 years; and transitional cell carcinoma of the right ureter at age 58 years. Axial contrast-enhanced CT <b>(a)</b> and fused PET/CT <b>(b)</b> images show an ill-defined FDG-avid thickening of the transverse duodenum (arrows) invading the pancreas and mesentery. The patient was diagnosed with a second primary duodenal adenocarcinoma. He had germline mutations of <i>MSH2</i> and <i>MSH6.</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig13a.jpeg" height="1240" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Pancreatic adenocarcinoma in a 56-year-old man who presented with symptoms of anemia. He was treated for sebaceous adenomas in his 40s and for duodenal cancer at age 47 years. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a 5-cm ill-defined hypoattenuating mass (arrows), representing adenocarcinoma, in the pancreatic tail. The tumor occludes the splenic vein (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) and encases the splenic artery (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). The patient was found to have a germline <i>MSH2</i> mutation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig13b.jpeg" height="1240" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Pancreatic adenocarcinoma in a 56-year-old man who presented with symptoms of anemia. He was treated for sebaceous adenomas in his 40s and for duodenal cancer at age 47 years. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a 5-cm ill-defined hypoattenuating mass (arrows), representing adenocarcinoma, in the pancreatic tail. The tumor occludes the splenic vein (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) and encases the splenic artery (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). The patient was found to have a germline <i>MSH2</i> mutation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig14a.jpeg" height="1410" width="1224" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Hilar cholangiocarcinoma in a 61-year-old man who presented with findings of obstructive jaundice. He was treated for colon cancer 19 years earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>b</b> obtained at a slightly different level than <b>a</b>) show diffusely dilated bile ducts terminating at a hilar mass (arrows), representing hilar cholangiocarcinoma. The patient was found to have an <i>MLH1</i> mutation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig14b.jpeg" height="1410" width="1224" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Hilar cholangiocarcinoma in a 61-year-old man who presented with findings of obstructive jaundice. He was treated for colon cancer 19 years earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>b</b> obtained at a slightly different level than <b>a</b>) show diffusely dilated bile ducts terminating at a hilar mass (arrows), representing hilar cholangiocarcinoma. The patient was found to have an <i>MLH1</i> mutation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig15a.jpeg" height="1814" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Glioblastoma in a 66-year-old man who presented with new seizures. He was treated for colon cancer 19 years earlier. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a 5-cm mass (arrows), representing glioblastoma, in the left temporal lobe. The tumor caused an 8-mm left-to-right midline shift and a mass effect on the left cerebral peduncle. The patient was found to have an <i>MSH2</i> mutation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170075/asset/images/large/rg.2018170075.fig15b.jpeg" height="1814" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Glioblastoma in a 66-year-old man who presented with new seizures. He was treated for colon cancer 19 years earlier. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a 5-cm mass (arrows), representing glioblastoma, in the left temporal lobe. The tumor caused an 8-mm left-to-right midline shift and a mass effect on the left cerebral peduncle. The patient was found to have an <i>MSH2</i> mutation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170075&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Nagy R, Sweet K, Eng C. Highly penetrant hereditary cancer syndromes. <em>Oncogene</em> 2004;23(38):6445–6470.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/sj.onc.1207714">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15322516/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Highly+penetrant+hereditary+cancer+syndromes&amp;author=R+Nagy&amp;author=K+Sweet&amp;author=C+Eng&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=Oncogene&amp;pages=6445-6470&amp;doi=10.1038%2Fsj.onc.1207714&amp;pmid=15322516">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hampel H, Frankel WL, Martin E, et al. Screening for the Lynch syndrome (hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer). <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2005;352(18):1851–1860.</div><di